ce:section.ce:para:
Room temperature photoluminescence (PL) measurements are performed to further investigate the interaction between the Chl-CQDs and MoS2 crystals. Fig. 2l shows the PL spectra of MoS2/Chl-CQDs heterostructure, bare MoS2 crystal, and Chl-CQDs film under an excitation wavelength of 525 nm. The spectrum peaks at 627 nm, and 676 nm in the heterostructure correspond well with the single components of the materials. The MoS2/Chl-CQDs heterostructure exhibits a noticeable variation in photoluminescence (PL) intensity and bathochromic shift compared to the bare MoS2 crystal, with peak positions at 617 nm and 667 nm shifting to 627 nm and 676 nm, respectively. This observation strongly suggests the occurrence of charge transfer between the MoS2 and Chl-CQDs, thereby confirming the successful integration of Chl-CQDs onto the MoS2 crystals. The band gap and energy levels of Chl-CQDs and MoS2 are determined from the onset absorptions of the UV–vis spectra and ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS). According to the initial absorption peak of the UV–vis absorption spectrum, the optical band gap (Eg
                     ) of Chl-CQDs and MoS2 can be determined as 1.95 eV and 2.3 eV respectively.[33] The highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) level is calculated to be 4.88 eV for MoS2 and 5.90 eV for Chl-CQDs calculated via UPS measurements (Fig. S6).[34] The lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) levels of MoS2 and Chl-CQDs are further estimated to be −2.58 eV and −3.95 eV, respectively, through the combination of their respective HOMO levels and energy band gaps. As shown in Fig. 3
                     a, based on the band alignment principle, the holes/electrons from Chl-CQDs/MoS2 are spontaneously injected into the n-type MoS2 and p-type Chl-CQDs layer. This injected process enables MoS2 and Chl-CQDs to act as efficient charge traps for capturing and releasing intrinsic carriers, thereby generating a controllable built-in electric field (Ebi
                     ) at the Chl-CQDs/MoS2 interface and inducing charge self-trapping memory behavior in such devices. We refer to such a heterostructure as a “reverse” type-II heterostructure. In contrast, the traditional type-II heterostructure typically involves the spontaneous injection of holes from QDs into p-type semiconductors materials with negligible charge self-trapping behaviors.

In summary, the designed “reverse” type-II Chl-CQDs/MoS2-based blue-light BIVN as a single device integrated with photo-sensing, photo-memory, and visual pain computation is confirmed. It demonstrates a novel synergistic absorption behavior and charge-self-trapping carrier transport mechanism (leading to a tunable Ebi
                     ) within the mixed-dimensional heterostructure. The key photoelectric characteristics of R and D* of heterotransistors are improved by over 100,000 times than pristine devices, and also show a high R ∼1300 A/W and D*∼3.8*1012 Jones under an ultra-low blue-light power density ∼35.9 μw/cm2 with 450 nm. Typical memory behaviors with a high on/off ratio ∼104 and basic VN functions are also demonstrated. Furthermore, attributed to the enhanced charge self-trapping effect and Ebi
                      strength within the heterostructure, the blockade functions and adaptation of visual pain are successfully simulated, which the maximum blocking degree is up to 35 % (light pulse: 280μW cm−2 and width of 3.5 s). The findings demonstrate the Chl-CQDs/MoS2-based adaptive BIVN has a great advantage in early-warning systems and/or risk mitigation strategies for preserving human eyesight.
